Decrypng Encrypted Array of Characters Using
Ghidra Scripts
In this blog, I will be explaining how to leverage ghidra scripts to decrypt the
encrypted strings in a binary.
Malware authors store the crical strings/shellcode in the .data or. rdata
secon of the binary in encrypted format to evade detecon. Furthermore, the
characters of the strings are stored as the array of characters to make the stac
analysis complex. One such instance has been observed in one of the binaries
that I analysed recently.
This was part of one of the challenges from Hack the box named Lockpick3.0
(a sample wrien based out of Locky Ransomware) in which a memory image
has been obtained from a ransomware aected ubuntu machine. The malicious
binary which aected the machine has been retrieved.
On analysing the binary, XOR decrypon loop for more than 10 strings have
been observed. This XOR decrypon results in the URL for command-and-
control server, second stage decrypon key, folders to encrypt, path to upload,
ransomware note and so on.
An Excerpt of the decompiled code is provided below.
Looking at the mulple calls to FUN_001029ca with dierent addresses from
the data secon as the rst parameter and the funcon that decrypts the
string.
The decrypon loop XORs each byte of the input with a corresponding key.
Looking at the overwhelming amount of the encrypted strings in the binary, I
have decided to write a ghidra script that takes address, size of the string and
key as a parameter and return the corresponding string in the ascii format and
was able to successfully retrieve the strings within no me.
The code can be downloaded from the GitHub link
hps://github.com/vadhyar/Reverse_engineering/blob/master/strings_decryp
on.py
On decrypng the bytes at one of the addresses,
Script in Acon:
Copy the code in the ghidras Script manager
Run the script
Script prompts to enter the address of the array, size of the array and the
key to decrypt.
Looking at the ghidras script console, we can observe that the string
has been decrypted and provided in the ascii format
This script makes it easier to obtain the deobfuscated/decrypted form of the
strings in the binary.
Conclusion: Ghidra Scripts always comes handy when working with samples
with mulple obfuscaon loops. This reduces the me consumpon for
deobfuscaon and saves me for further analysis.
A similar technique of Mulple XOR encrypons is seen in ransomwares like
Locky and Cryptowares. This script might be helpful in handling the variants of
ransomwares with mulple encrypon rounes.
